text: It's funny you bring up trading axioms and trading wisdom. There's so much bad stuff and stuff that doesn't pass the basic back test and research that gets passed down. And I really believe one of the ones that's really pernicious is this idea of focusing on win-loss ratios and at the trade level and streaks of trades and what's not possible. What people have to realize is, and this is really important to timing the trade or figuring out when it's not working. When you are calibrated with a regime in a market, you can literally have 20 winning trades in a row. Now, over the long haul, those numbers will average out to whatever the historical average is. But when you're synchronized perfectly with the current regime, then you will win, win, win, win, win, win, win. For me, the tale has always been is, is this starting to be hard money? I noticed this. Going... Going into the end of 2017, 2018, I noticed that it was all of a sudden, vol wasn't going down. These products weren't going down. I'm like, damn, you can almost sell weekly puts or bi-weekly puts on VXX and come out with a profit. So in other words, the cost of, from a big picture perspective, all of a sudden you got a positive carry on insurance, right? And so when that starts to happen, then you're like, okay, this is crowded. That's my take on it. It's just crowded. It's just too many people know it, but it's just too many people know it. And so I think that's what I'm trying to do, is I'm trying to get people to think about it. The pejoratively coined target manager made $50 million waking up and shorting TVX every day. And so once that got out there, I mean, there are a whole YouTube shows Corey dedicated to, I just short vol blindly. I just do it. I'm just the short vol. So like I, all I do is sell vol. So that's one thing, but then it starts to manifest itself in the actual volatility on these products and just the price performance. And so at that point, it's like, okay, you know what? It's time to pack up and go home onto something else onto the next table.
